            <pb n="1"/>
            <p rend="align(center)">Israelites of <placeName>Cleveland</placeName></p>
            <p>To the Editor of the Occident.</p>
            <p>In reference to the report concerning the Israelitish <add>?</add><lb/>
                <add>?</add> congregation of <placeName>Cleveland, Ohio</placeName> in No 6
                    <add>?</add> of the Occident<lb/> we request you to notice a designed
                    <add>?</add> of your reporter <persName>B. L. F. Mr Isidor<lb/>
                    Kalisch</persName> who has been educated as Rabbi in the highest <hi
                    rend="underline">Yeshiboth</hi> under<lb/> the highest Talmudical authorities,
                and as a theologian with<lb/> universities of <placeName>Berlin</placeName> &amp;
                    <placeName>Breslaw</placeName>, who moreover was a contributor<lb/> to various
                learned periodicals in German, is among <add>?</add> not only<lb/>
                <hi rend="underline">Hazan</hi>, but likewise, Rabbi, Preacher, and religious
                instructor. We who<lb/> are thoroughly acquainted with the officers of both the
                congregation of<lb/> this place promise you speedily a detailed statement of the
                rise<lb/> and development of the same. In conclusion we cannot avoid
                expres-<lb/>sing our surprise, that you Mr Editor, who ought to be acquainted<lb/>
                with our congregational affairs no less than with <persName>Mr
                Kalisch</persName><lb/> who was lately your correspondent for the Occident,
                should<lb/> have known better how to appreciate his services, that to accept<lb/>
                the communication of <persName>B. L. F.</persName> which contains <add>?</add>
                misrepresen-<lb/>tations and is intended merely to praise himself, without
                correcting the<lb/> same. In the hope that you will insert this letter at once<lb/>
                in the Occident we remain respectfully yours.</p>
            <p rend="align(right)"><persName>J. Englhart</persName> President</p>
            <p rend="align(right)"><persName>C Koch</persName> Vice President</p>
            <p rend="align(right)"><persName>G A Davis</persName> Treasurer</p>
            <p rend="align(center)">
                <persName>D Cauffman</persName>
            </p>
            <p rend="align(right)">
                <persName>David Henfer</persName>
            </p>
            <p rend="align(right)"><persName>Samuel Loeb</persName> Trustees</p>
            <p rend="align(right)">
                <persName>F. J. Cohn</persName>
            </p>
            <p rend="align(right)"><persName>A Schwab</persName> let President of<lb/> Israeli
                    <add>?</add><lb/> Israel congrn.</p>
            <p>
                <placeName>Cleveland</placeName>
                <date>Sep 12. 5612</date>
            </p>
            <pb n="2"/>
            <p><hi rend="underline">Not by the Editor</hi>. We indeed discovered that <persName>B.
                    L. F.</persName> wished to place<lb/> his own labours somewhat prominently
                before the public; but this we<lb/> did not deem any insult to <persName>Mr
                    Kalisch</persName>; as little as the statement that<lb/> he was Hazan and
                Teacher, as we have in our own person filled both<lb/> these functions, and were
                nevertheless the preacher of the older congregation<lb/> of
                    <placeName>Philadelphia</placeName> for twenty years, without any other title
                than Heizan,<lb/> To be <add>?</add> preaching was gratuitous, and was not
                    <add>?</add> in the<lb/> contract which was drawn up by the managers of the
                congregation,<lb/> but <add>?</add> there is no insult in one being called the <hi
                    rend="underline">Hazan</hi> of any<lb/> public body, especially in
                    <placeName>America</placeName> when, until the arrival of<lb/>
                <persName>Rabbi A. Rice</persName> of <placeName>Baltimore</placeName> not long
                since it was the highest<lb/>
                <sic>ecclessiastical</sic> title among us. We have borne it for upward of<lb/>
                twenty one years, and thought it no degradation, though we<lb/> occasionally acted
                as Rabbi &amp; preached not a few sermons,<lb/> with what success is not for us to
                say. <add>?</add> we must that<lb/> on friends at <placeName>Cleveland</placeName>
                will discharge us from any <add>?</add> of<lb/> slighting them or <persName>Mr
                    Kalisch</persName>, when contributors we have<lb/> from time to time inserted in
                the Occident <add>?</add> have thing we<lb/> must state, that if <persName>Mr
                    K</persName> should be attacked hereafter (but<lb/>
                <hi rend="underline">not</hi> in the Occident as our work has a higher aim than
                destroying<lb/> observation,) it will be his own fault for his extremely
                injurious<lb/> course in the divine case, since he has not <add>?</add> till he<lb/>
                succeeded in appearing before the public in the Asmonean as the<lb/> accuser of
                    <persName>Mr Joseph Levy</persName>. For our part we are tired of the
                controversy<lb/> it is a subject for a <add>שאלה</add> (Question) to the highest
                authorities in <placeName>Europe</placeName>;<lb/> and we will abide by their
                decision; but no man who understands<lb/> the nature of Jewish jurisprudence will
                for a moment contend that<lb/> either Plain dealer, Asmonean or Occident is a proper
                vehicle to</p>
